      <!-- ══ Problem 1 (math) ══ -->
      <div class="problem">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">Problem 1</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Continuity &amp; Mixed Partial Derivatives</span>
          <span class="pts">10 pts</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <div class="context-box">Consider the function below, defined piecewise at the origin.</div>
          <div class="define-block">
            \[f(x,y)=\begin{cases}\dfrac{xy(x^2-y^2)}{x^2+y^2}, & (x,y)\neq(0,0)\\[6pt] 0, & (x,y)=(0,0).\end{cases}\]
          </div>
          <ol class="parts">
            <li><span class="part-label">(a)</span><span>Show that \(f\) is continuous at \((0,0)\). <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(b)</span><span>Using the limit definition, compute \(f_x(0,0)\) and \(f_y(0,0)\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(c)</span><span>Away from the origin, \(f_x(0,y)=-y\) and \(f_y(x,0)=x\). Use these to compute \(f_{xy}(0,0)\) and \(f_{yx}(0,0)\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(d)</span><span>Your two answers in (c) differ. Why does this not contradict Clairaut's theorem? <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
          </ol>
          <div class="ans-toggle">
            <button class="ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns('a1')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="answer" id="a1">
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(a) Continuity</div>
                In polar form \(x=r\cos\theta,y=r\sin\theta\): \(|f|=\left|\dfrac{r^2\cos\theta\sin\theta\,r^2(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta)}{r^2}\right|=r^2|\cos\theta\sin\theta(\cos^2\theta-\sin^2\theta)|\le r^2\to0\) as \(r\to0\).
                <div class="key-result">\(\lim_{(x,y)\to(0,0)}f(x,y)=0=f(0,0)\) — continuous ✓</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(b) First partials at origin</div>
                \(f_x(0,0)=\lim_{h\to0}\dfrac{f(h,0)-0}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\dfrac{0}{h}=0\). Similarly \(f_y(0,0)=\lim_{k\to0}\dfrac{f(0,k)}{k}=0\).
                <div class="key-result">\(f_x(0,0)=0,\quad f_y(0,0)=0.\)</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(c) Mixed partials at origin</div>
                \(f_{xy}(0,0)=\dfrac{\partial}{\partial y}f_x\Big|_{(0,0)}=\lim_{k\to0}\dfrac{f_x(0,k)-f_x(0,0)}{k}=\lim_{k\to0}\dfrac{-k-0}{k}=-1.\)
                \(f_{yx}(0,0)=\lim_{h\to0}\dfrac{f_y(h,0)-f_y(0,0)}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\dfrac{h-0}{h}=+1.\)
                <div class="key-result">\(f_{xy}(0,0)=-1\neq f_{yx}(0,0)=+1.\)</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(d) Why no contradiction</div>
                Clairaut's theorem requires the mixed partials \(f_{xy}\) and \(f_{yx}\) to be <em>continuous</em> in a neighbourhood of the point. For this \(f\), the mixed partials exist everywhere but are <strong>not continuous at the origin</strong>, so the hypothesis fails and equality is not guaranteed.
                <div class="ans-note">This is the classic textbook counterexample showing continuity of the mixed partials is essential, not optional.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ Problem 2 (flavor) ══ -->
      <div class="problem">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">Problem 2</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Drone Terrain Survey — Critical Points <span class="badge-hard">HARD</span></span>
          <span class="pts">12 pts</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <div class="context-box">
            A survey drone maps the elevation of a small valley. The terrain height (in metres) above a reference plane is modelled by
          </div>
          <div class="define-block">
            \[h(x,y)=x^3 - 3xy + y^3.\]
          </div>
          <ol class="parts">
            <li><span class="part-label">(a)</span><span>Compute \(\nabla h\) and find all critical points (where the drone reads zero slope). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(b)</span><span>Compute the Hessian \(H\). Classify each critical point as a local max, local min, or saddle. <span class="pts">5 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(c)</span><span>At the point \((1,1)\), find the direction of steepest ascent and the maximum rate of climb. <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(d)</span><span>Give the equation of the tangent plane to the terrain at \((1,1)\). <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
          </ol>
          <div class="ans-toggle">
            <button class="ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns('a2')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="answer" id="a2">
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(a) Critical points</div>
                \(\nabla h=(3x^2-3y,\;-3x+3y^2)\). Set both to zero: \(y=x^2\) and \(x=y^2\). Substituting: \(x=x^4\Rightarrow x(x^3-1)=0\Rightarrow x=0\) or \(x=1\).
                <div class="key-result">Critical points: \((0,0)\) and \((1,1)\).</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(b) Hessian classification</div>
                \(H=\begin{pmatrix}6x&-3\\-3&6y\end{pmatrix}\), \(\det H=36xy-9\).
                At \((0,0)\): \(\det H=-9<0\) → <strong>saddle point</strong>.
                At \((1,1)\): \(\det H=36-9=27>0\) and \(h_{xx}=6>0\) → <strong>local minimum</strong>.
                <div class="key-result">\((0,0)\) saddle; \((1,1)\) local min.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(c) Steepest ascent at (1,1)</div>
                \(\nabla h(1,1)=(3-3,\;-3+3)=(0,0)\) — wait, \((1,1)\) is the critical point, so the slope is zero in every direction. Re-reading: at a critical point there is no direction of ascent.
                <div class="key-result">At \((1,1)\) the gradient is \(\mathbf 0\); the rate of climb is \(0\) in all directions (it's the valley floor).</div>
                <div class="ans-note">Trick sub-part: recognising that the gradient vanishes at a critical point is the point. If asked at a non-critical point like \((2,1)\): \(\nabla h=(9,-3)\), steepest-ascent direction \(\tfrac{1}{\sqrt{90}}(9,-3)\), max rate \(\sqrt{90}\).</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(d) Tangent plane at (1,1)</div>
                \(h(1,1)=1-3+1=-1\), \(\nabla h(1,1)=(0,0)\).
                <div class="key-result">\(z=-1+0(x-1)+0(y-1)\;\Rightarrow\; z=-1\) (a horizontal plane, as expected at a local min).</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ Problem 3 (math) ══ -->
      <div class="problem">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">Problem 3</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Multivariable Chain Rule</span>
          <span class="pts">10 pts</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <div class="context-box">Let \(z=f(x,y)=x^2y\), where \(x\) and \(y\) depend on two parameters:</div>
          <div class="define-block">
            \[x(s,t)=s\cos t,\qquad y(s,t)=s\sin t.\]
          </div>
          <ol class="parts">
            <li><span class="part-label">(a)</span><span>Use the chain rule to find \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}\) in terms of \(s\) and \(t\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(b)</span><span>Find \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial t}\) in terms of \(s\) and \(t\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(c)</span><span>Verify your answer to (a) by substituting first to get \(z(s,t)\) directly, then differentiating. <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(d)</span><span>Evaluate \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}\) at \((s,t)=(2,\pi/4)\). <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
          </ol>
          <div class="ans-toggle">
            <button class="ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns('a3')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="answer" id="a3">
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(a) ∂z/∂s</div>
                \(z_x=2xy,\;z_y=x^2\); \(x_s=\cos t,\;y_s=\sin t\).
                \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}=2xy\cos t+x^2\sin t\). Substitute \(x=s\cos t,y=s\sin t\):
                \(=2(s\cos t)(s\sin t)\cos t+(s\cos t)^2\sin t=2s^2\cos^2t\sin t+s^2\cos^2t\sin t.\)
                <div class="key-result">\(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}=3s^2\cos^2 t\,\sin t.\)</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(b) ∂z/∂t</div>
                \(x_t=-s\sin t,\;y_t=s\cos t\).
                \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial t}=2xy(-s\sin t)+x^2(s\cos t)=2(s\cos t)(s\sin t)(-s\sin t)+(s\cos t)^2(s\cos t).\)
                \(=-2s^3\cos t\sin^2 t+s^3\cos^3 t.\)
                <div class="key-result">\(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial t}=s^3\cos t\,(\cos^2 t-2\sin^2 t).\)</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(c) Verify by direct substitution</div>
                \(z=x^2y=(s\cos t)^2(s\sin t)=s^3\cos^2 t\sin t\). Then \(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}=3s^2\cos^2 t\sin t\) ✓ — matches (a).
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(d) Evaluate at (2, π/4)</div>
                \(\cos^2(\pi/4)=\tfrac12,\;\sin(\pi/4)=\tfrac{1}{\sqrt2}\). So \(3(4)(\tfrac12)(\tfrac{1}{\sqrt2})=\dfrac{6}{\sqrt2}=3\sqrt2.\)
                <div class="key-result">\(\dfrac{\partial z}{\partial s}\Big|_{(2,\pi/4)}=3\sqrt{2}\approx4.243.\)</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ Problem 4 (flavor) ══ -->
      <div class="problem">
        <div class="problem-header">
          <span class="problem-num">Problem 4</span>
          <span class="problem-title">Chemical Concentration &amp; Directional Change</span>
          <span class="pts">8 pts</span>
        </div>
        <div class="problem-body">
          <div class="context-box">
            A pollutant disperses across a lake surface. Its concentration (in ppm) at position \((x,y)\) is
          </div>
          <div class="define-block">
            \[C(x,y)=100\,e^{-(x^2+2y^2)}.\]
            A sensor drifts through the point \(P=(1,1)\).
          </div>
          <ol class="parts">
            <li><span class="part-label">(a)</span><span>Compute \(\nabla C\) at \(P=(1,1)\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(b)</span><span>The sensor moves in the direction \(\mathbf v=(3,4)\). Find the rate of change of concentration it measures at \(P\). <span class="pts">3 pts</span></span></li>
            <li><span class="part-label">(c)</span><span>In which direction should the sensor move from \(P\) to record the fastest <em>decrease</em> in concentration? <span class="pts">2 pts</span></span></li>
          </ol>
          <div class="ans-toggle">
            <button class="ans-btn" onclick="toggleAns('a4')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="answer" id="a4">
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(a) Gradient at P</div>
                \(C_x=100e^{-(x^2+2y^2)}(-2x)=-200x\,C/100\cdots\) more directly: \(C_x=-200x\,e^{-(x^2+2y^2)}\), \(C_y=-400y\,e^{-(x^2+2y^2)}\).
                At \((1,1)\): \(e^{-(1+2)}=e^{-3}\). So \(C_x=-200e^{-3},\;C_y=-400e^{-3}\).
                <div class="key-result">\(\nabla C(1,1)=-200e^{-3}\,(1,\,2)\approx(-9.96,\,-19.91)\) ppm/unit.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(b) Directional rate along v=(3,4)</div>
                Unit vector \(\mathbf u=\tfrac{1}{5}(3,4)\). \(D_{\mathbf u}C=\nabla C\cdot\mathbf u=-200e^{-3}(1,2)\cdot\tfrac15(3,4)=-200e^{-3}\cdot\tfrac{3+8}{5}=-200e^{-3}\cdot\tfrac{11}{5}.\)
                <div class="key-result">\(D_{\mathbf u}C(1,1)=-440e^{-3}\approx-21.9\) ppm per unit distance.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="ans-part">
                <div class="ans-part-label">(c) Fastest decrease</div>
                Concentration decreases fastest in the direction of \(-\nabla C\), i.e. \(+(1,2)\) normalised.
                <div class="key-result">Direction: \(\dfrac{1}{\sqrt5}(1,2)\). (Maximum rate of decrease \(=\|\nabla C\|=200\sqrt5\,e^{-3}\approx22.3\) ppm/unit.)</div>
                <div class="ans-note">Note the gradient points "downhill" here because both partials are negative — moving along \(+(1,2)\) heads away from the concentration peak at the origin.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

